-- Mahindra Advances as India's Sensex Index Climbs to Highest in 30 Months
-- Rajhkumar K Shaaw
-- 2010-08-06T04:59:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-06/mahindra-advances-as-india-s-sensex-index-climbs-to-highest-in-30-months.html

          
          
             India’s benchmark stock index rose to
the highest in 2 1/2 years as increases tax collections signaled
consumer spending may be strengthening with rising incomes.  
 Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd. , a tractor maker, climbed the most
in a week after a newspaper reported it will build a new factory.
Essar Shipping Ports & Logistics Ltd. advanced to a two-year
high after raising $280 million selling convertible bonds to its
parent. India’s direct tax collection between April and July
rose 16 percent, about five times faster than in the year
earlier period.  
 “The increased tax collection shows that people will have
more money to spend and invest,” said  Alex Mathews , head of
research at Geojit BNP Paribas Financial Services Ltd. in
Kochi. “The demand outlook for the auto sector remains strong.
It is a good sign that companies are increasing capacities.”  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 35.26, or 0.2 percent, to 18,208.09 at 10:27 a.m. in
Mumbai, on course for a 1.9 percent gain this week. The S&P CNX
 Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange rose 0.3 percent to
5,460.55. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.3 percent to 2,320.71.  
 Mahindra Plant  
 Mahindra rose 1.7 percent to 656 rupees, set for its
steepest advance in a week. The company plans to spend as much
as 18 billion rupees ($390 million) to set up a new tractor-
building plant in the south Indian state of Tamil Nadu, Business
Standard reported, citing  Pawan Goenka , president of the
automotive and farm equipment unit. Goenka didn’t answer a call
to his cell phone seeking comment on the report.  
 Essar Shipping  jumped 6.1 percent to 115.3 rupees, set for
its highest close since August 2008. The nation’s second-largest
marine transport company by market value after raising $280
million selling convertible bonds to its parent to buy ships and
expand ports.  
 India’s direct tax collection between April and July
climbed to 856.5 billion rupees from 739.9 billion rupees a year
earlier, the country’s finance ministry said yesterday.
Corporate tax collections increased 21 percent. Total levies
collected rose 3.3 percent a year earlier.  
 Overseas  funds  bought a net  7.42 billion rupees  ($160.4
million) of Indian equities on August 4, the 22nd straight day
that purchases have exceeded sales, raising their total
investments in the stocks this year to 510.2 billion rupees,
according to the nation’s market regulator.  
 Inflows from overseas reached a record 834.2 billion rupees
in 2009, exceeding the high set two years ago in local currency
terms, as the biggest advance in 18 years lured foreign funds.
They sold a record 529.9 billion rupees of shares in 2008,
triggering a record annual decline.  
